Dynamic Watermark System
Overview

The platform now includes a dynamic watermark overlay above the video player.

Purpose:

Leak tracing
Camera recording deterrence
Discourage video sharing
Identify the student account responsible for leaked content
Watermark Data

The backend sends watermark data from:

GET /api/lessons/{lesson_id}/mux-token/

Watermark includes:

Username
Email
Device ID

Example:

"watermark": {
  "username": "mo7",
  "email": "student@example.com",
  "device_id": "device-id-value"
}
Watermark Device ID

The backend reads device ID from the request header:

x-device-id

If the header is missing:

unknown

This means the frontend must send:

x-device-id

with authenticated requests.

Frontend Watermark Rendering

The watermark is displayed inside:

CourseLessons.tsx

Above:

MuxPlayer

The video container is now:

relative

This allows the watermark to appear above the player using absolute positioning.

Watermark Visibility Design

The watermark was intentionally designed to be:

Very light
Semi-transparent
Small
Not disturbing for the student
Hard enough to remove completely
Visible enough for leak tracing

Style characteristics:

Low opacity
Small text
Slight blur background
Text shadow
No pointer events
Select disabled
Moving Watermark Behavior

The watermark is not fixed.

It moves between multiple positions over time.

Example positions:

Top right
Upper left/center area
Middle area
Lower area
Bottom right

Movement interval:

Every 9 seconds

Purpose:

Makes cropping harder
Makes hiding the watermark harder
Reduces the chance that a leaked video removes all watermark evidence
Watermark Displayed Text

The watermark can include:

username | email | device_id | current_time

Example:

mo7 | momomomo7@gmail.com | abc123device | 05:15

Only part of the device ID may be shown to keep the overlay short.

Watermark Security Philosophy

The watermark does not prevent recording completely.

Instead, it provides:

Accountability
Leak tracing
Psychological deterrence
Evidence in leaked recordings

This is especially important before enabling paid DRM.

